Problems found in the snippet  
──────────────────────────────

1. Leaks the password  
   • `res.json({ …user.rows[0], password: user.rows[0].password })` returns the column that should **never** leave the server – even if it is hashed.  
   • By using the spread operator and then adding `password` again, the password is guaranteed to be present in the response.

2. Missing error & edge-case handling  
   • If the query returns no rows, `user.rows[0]` is `undefined`, causing `TypeError: Cannot read property 'password' of undefined`.  
   • Any database or runtime error becomes an unhandled promise-rejection because the handler is not wrapped in `try/​catch` (Express 4 does not catch async errors).

3. Lack of input validation / sanitisation  
   • `req.params.id` is accepted as-is; non-numeric input (e.g., `"abc"`) is silently sent to the DB.  
   • Although the query is parameterised (`$1`), accepting invalid types can still lead to unexpected behaviour or DoS (e.g., very large numbers).

4. Insecure direct object reference (IDOR) / Missing authorisation  
   • Any logged-out caller (or any logged-in caller, depending on other middleware) can request `/api/users/1`, `/api/users/2`, … and read every account record.  
   • There is no check that the caller owns the resource or has adequate privileges (e.g., admin).

5. Over-broad “SELECT *”  
   • Pulls every column even when most are not needed (wastes bandwidth, risks leaking more sensitive data if additional columns are added later).

6. No explicit HTTP status codes  
   • Always responds with 200 even when the user is not found or an error occurs.

7. Minor style / best-practice issues  
   • No `await` timeout / cancellation.  
   • No connection release if using a client pool manually.  
   • The route name exposes a sequential integer identifier, making enumeration easier.

Recommended fix  
───────────────

```js
// Example with Express 4/5, pg, and typical middle-ware
app.get(
  '/api/users/:id',
  authenticateUser,                // verifies JWT/session
  allowSelfOrRole('admin'),        // authorisation layer
  async (req, res, next) => {
    try {
      // ----- 1. Validate input ------------------------------------------
      const id = Number.parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
      if (Number.isNaN(id) || id < 1) {
        return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid user id' });
      }

      // ----- 2. Query only required columns -----------------------------
      const { rows } = await db.query(
        'SELECT id, username, email, created_at FROM users WHERE id = $1',
        [id]
      );

      // ----- 3. Handle “not-found” --------------------------------------
      if (rows.length === 0) {
        return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
      }

      // ----- 4. Return safe payload -------------------------------------
      return res.status(200).json(rows[0]);
    } catch (err) {
      // Express error handler
      next(err);
    }
  }
);
```

What the fix addresses  
──────────────────────

• Removes `password` (and any other sensitive columns) from the payload.  
• Adds authentication + authorisation to prevent IDOR.  
• Validates and sanitises `id` input; returns 400 for bad input.  
• Returns 404 when record is absent.  
• Uses `try/catch` so errors propagate to the central error handler instead of crashing the process.  
• Selects only explicit columns (principle of least privilege).  
• Sends the correct HTTP status codes.  
• Keeps database query parameterised.  
• Input validation also thwarts potential DoS and unexpected type coercion attacks.

Optional additional improvements  
────────────────────────────────

• Rate-limit the endpoint to reduce account enumeration attempts.  
• Consider UUIDs or opaque IDs instead of sequential integers.  
• Add caching headers (if appropriate) or ETag support.  
• Apply a request-schema validator such as `Joi` or `zod` to keep validation declarative.  
• Log access to sensitive resources for audit purposes.
